<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,991,1738]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,991,1017]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Male unknown. Female with frontal facets moderately enlarged (J 
<number box="[1074,1105,992,1018]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="92.0">92</number>
<figureCitation box="[1105,1175,992,1018]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1761,1785]" captionTargetBox="[155,1430,197,1734]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[155,1432,197,1735]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Inner male genitalia (phallus). 1. C. fimbriatus agg.; 2. C. absconditus spec. nov.; 3. C. clarus; 4. C. immanis spec. nov.; 5. C. juliae; Abbreviations: lower ej. d., lower ejaculatory ductuli; mtdp, membranous tip of distiphallus; php, phallic processes; phs, phallic shaft; tdp, tip of distiphallus; upper ej. d., upper ejaculatory duct; 6. C. latifrons. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184951/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[1159,1175,992,1018]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A); frons at narrowest point 
<number box="[219,307,1032,1058]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1.35" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="1.2">1.2–1.5</number>
times diameter of largest frontal facet; flagellum dark brown; legs entirely dark brown; pulvilli of all legs of same size, shorter than distitarsus; hairs on femora light to mid brown in holo- and 
<typeStatus box="[1327,1432,1072,1098]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">paratype</typeStatus>
; hairs on thorax and abdomen mid to dark brown; posterior/posterodorsal hair fringe on mid femora (
<figureCitation box="[1334,1422,1112,1138]" captionStart="FIGURES 79 – 80" captionStartId="16.[151,269,1323,1347]" captionTargetBox="[498,1093,774,1296]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[491,1096,761,1299]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 79 – 80. Right mid femur in posterodorsal view with posterior / posterodorsal setal row (other hairs omitted) of female. 79. C. argenteus; 80. C. spurius. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184959/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[1389,1422,1112,1138]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="79.0">79</number>
</figureCitation>
); hind femur with apical hairs of pdsr extending as far as apex; abdominal tergites dark brown; ovipositor as in 
<figureCitation box="[151,286,1192,1218]" captionStart="FIGURES 63 – 75" captionStartId="15.[151,269,1326,1350]" captionTargetBox="[155,1430,197,1295]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[155,1432,194,1302]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 63 – 75. Female ovipositor. 63 – 64. C. spurius lateral view; 65 – 66. C. argenteus lateral view; 67. C. spurius dorsal view; 68. C. marki spec. nov. dorsal view; 69. C. marki spec. nov. lateral view; 70. C. decorus lateral view; 71. C. indistinctus lateral view; 72. C. longicaudis lateral view; 73. C. brevicaudis lateral view; 74. C. indistinctus dorsal view; 75. C. brevicaudis dorsal view. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184957/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Figs 
<number box="[209,286,1192,1218]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="65.5" valueMax="66.0" valueMin="65.0">65–66</number>
</figureCitation>
. No 
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[340,404,1192,1218]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">DNA</collectionCode>
barcode could be obtained.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,991,1738]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,360,1231,1257]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Annotations:</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[427,529,1232,1258]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
and the 
<typeStatus box="[638,739,1232,1258]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">paratype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[784,935,1232,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Chalarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argenteus">
<emphasis box="[784,935,1232,1257]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">C. argenteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were obtained for study, as was the only reared specimen (ex. 
<taxonomicName box="[413,651,1272,1297]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Typhlocyba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quercus">
<emphasis box="[413,651,1272,1297]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Typhlocyba quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) mentioned in 
<bibRefCitation author="Jervis" box="[841,1003,1272,1298]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" refString="Jervis, M. A. (1992) A taxonomic revision of the pipunculid fly genus Chalarus Walker, with particular reference to the European fauna. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 105, 243 - 352." type="journal article" year="1992">
Jervis (
<number box="[930,994,1272,1298]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1992.0">1992</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The abdomen of the 
<typeStatus box="[1276,1378,1272,1298]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">holotype</typeStatus>
was removed in order to enable a detailed study of the shape of the ovipositor (
<figureCitation box="[1020,1108,1312,1338]" captionStart="FIGURES 63 – 75" captionStartId="15.[151,269,1326,1350]" captionTargetBox="[155,1430,197,1295]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[155,1432,194,1302]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 63 – 75. Female ovipositor. 63 – 64. C. spurius lateral view; 65 – 66. C. argenteus lateral view; 67. C. spurius dorsal view; 68. C. marki spec. nov. dorsal view; 69. C. marki spec. nov. lateral view; 70. C. decorus lateral view; 71. C. indistinctus lateral view; 72. C. longicaudis lateral view; 73. C. brevicaudis lateral view; 74. C. indistinctus dorsal view; 75. C. brevicaudis dorsal view. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184957/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[1075,1108,1312,1338]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="66.0">66</number>
</figureCitation>
). Unfortunately, the ovipositor suffered deformation in this process but its shape is still discernible. In the past, the ovipositor of the 
<typeStatus box="[151,252,1392,1418]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">paratype</typeStatus>
was dissected and placed in canada balsam. Today, the embedding medium is partly chipped off and the ovipositor lost. Based on adult morphology, 
<taxonomicName box="[711,859,1432,1457]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Chalarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argenteus">
<emphasis box="[711,859,1432,1457]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">C. argenteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
strongly resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[1093,1213,1432,1457]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Cephalops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spurius">
<emphasis box="[1093,1213,1432,1457]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">C. spurius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but normally has a slightly shorter and straighter tergite 
<number box="[592,607,1472,1498]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="9.0">9</number>
(ovipositor’s piercer), a slightly narrower frons and a slightly longer, paler and more strongly curved posterior/posterodorsal hair fringe on mid femora (compare 
<figureCitation box="[1283,1425,1512,1538]" captionStart="FIGURES 79 – 80" captionStartId="16.[151,269,1323,1347]" captionTargetBox="[498,1093,774,1296]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[491,1096,761,1299]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 79 – 80. Right mid femur in posterodorsal view with posterior / posterodorsal setal row (other hairs omitted) of female. 79. C. argenteus; 80. C. spurius. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184959/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Figs 
<number box="[1346,1425,1512,1538]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="79.5" valueMax="80.0" valueMin="79.0">79–80</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Jervis" box="[151,418,1552,1578]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" refString="Jervis, M. A. (1992) A taxonomic revision of the pipunculid fly genus Chalarus Walker, with particular reference to the European fauna. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 105, 243 - 352." type="journal article" year="1992">
Jervis (
<number box="[236,296,1552,1578]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1992.0">1992</number>
&amp; in litt.)
</bibRefCitation>
provides convincing larval/pupal evidence for an independence of the taxon by comparing the shape of the mandibles of second instar larva of 
<taxonomicName box="[844,992,1592,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Chalarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argenteus">
<emphasis box="[844,992,1592,1617]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">C. argenteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1050,1170,1592,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Cephalops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spurius">
<emphasis box="[1050,1170,1592,1617]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">C. spurius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(J 
<number box="[1197,1227,1592,1618]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="92.0">92</number>
<figureCitation box="[1227,1315,1592,1618]" captionStart="FIGURES 34 – 48" captionStartId="13.[151,269,1748,1772]" captionTargetBox="[155,1431,185,1721]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[155,1432,185,1722]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 34 – 48. Female ovipositor. 34. C. pughi ventral view; 35. C. basalis ventral view; Abbreviation: s 7, sternite 7; 36. C. pughi dorsal view; Abbreviations: t 7, tergite 7; t 8, tergite 8; t 9, tergite 9; 37. C. basalis dorsal view; 38. C. pughi lateral view; 39. C. basalis lateral view; 40. C. fimbriatus lateral view; 41. C. fimbriatus Form A lateral view; 42. C. fimbriatus Form B lateral view; 43. C. juliae dorsal view; 44. C. leticiae dorsal view; 45. C. juliae lateral view; 46. C. leticiae lateral view; 47. C. elegantulus lateral view; 48. C. latifrons lateral view. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184955/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Figs 
<number box="[1286,1315,1592,1618]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="38.0">38</number>
</figureCitation>
E &amp; Q–R) and the posterior spiracular plate of fully grown larva/puparium (J 
<number box="[937,967,1632,1658]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="92.0">92</number>
<figureCitation box="[967,1058,1632,1658]" captionStart="FIGURES 34 – 48" captionStartId="13.[151,269,1748,1772]" captionTargetBox="[155,1431,185,1721]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[155,1432,185,1722]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 34 – 48. Female ovipositor. 34. C. pughi ventral view; 35. C. basalis ventral view; Abbreviation: s 7, sternite 7; 36. C. pughi dorsal view; Abbreviations: t 7, tergite 7; t 8, tergite 8; t 9, tergite 9; 37. C. basalis dorsal view; 38. C. pughi lateral view; 39. C. basalis lateral view; 40. C. fimbriatus lateral view; 41. C. fimbriatus Form A lateral view; 42. C. fimbriatus Form B lateral view; 43. C. juliae dorsal view; 44. C. leticiae dorsal view; 45. C. juliae lateral view; 46. C. leticiae lateral view; 47. C. elegantulus lateral view; 48. C. latifrons lateral view. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184955/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Figs 
<number box="[1027,1058,1632,1658]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="40.0">40</number>
</figureCitation>
B &amp; 
<number box="[1116,1148,1632,1658]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="42.0">42</number>
E). Both features clearly differ from each other — note that the upper margin of the posterior spiracular plate of 
<taxonomicName box="[1183,1333,1672,1697]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Chalarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argenteus">
<emphasis box="[1183,1333,1672,1697]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">C. argenteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is partly covered with debris and hence not clearly visible.
</paragraph>
